# `<package>` — developer notes (template)

> Per-package `CLAUDE.md` template, specialised from
> **`docs/templates/CLAUDE.md.foundation`** (the parent
> `scripts`-collection template). When a new package is
> extracted from the collection, copy this file to
> `<package>/CLAUDE.md` and customise each section per the
> guidance below.
>
> This file is itself the worked example for the `account`
> package — the live `CLAUDE.md` in this repo was bootstrapped
> from it. Subsequent edits to either should be reflected in
> both during periodic audits (see `skills/audit.md`).

## 1. Scope

**Guide.** One paragraph: what does this package own? List
the data it stewards, the queries it answers, the side
effects it performs. Follow with a paragraph naming what is
**out of scope** so the boundary is explicit.

**Example (account).**
`account` is the identity foundation. Its scope is:

- the current Unix user's GPG / SSH keys, git config,
  sudoers
- the set of remote accounts registered with this host
  (each represented by a `<account>.pub` key under
  `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/account/{ssh,gpg}/`)
- read-only queries of the local platform (FQDN, host
  parts, online status)

Out of scope: configuration storage (that's `config`),
secret material (that's `secret`), repo orchestration
(that's `repo`), system-user provisioning (that's
`user`).

## 2. Repo conventions

**Guide.** Document the package's `bin/<name>` shape: is it
a self-contained dispatcher, or does it split into
`libexec/<name>/<verb>` files? Are subcommands inline or
plugin-loaded? Reference the rpk conventions, then call
out the package-specific deviations (if any).

**Example (account).**
Standard rpk per-package conventions: `bin/account`
dispatcher with `command:<verb>` functions, no plugin
loader. Subcommands are inline; there is no
`libexec/account/` because account's surface is small
enough that one self-contained dispatcher beats split
files.

## 3. Issue authoring

**Guide.** Reference `skills/features.md`,
`skills/bugs.md`, `skills/milestones.md`, and
`skills/audit.md` for the contracts. Note the bugs-before-
features rule, the test-in-the-same-commit rule, and the
PR-comment CI-failure channel.

**Example (account).**
See `skills/features.md`, `skills/bugs.md`,
`skills/milestones.md`, and `skills/audit.md`. Bugs come
before features at the same priority level; every new test
lands in the same commit as the change it covers; CI
failures get a PR-comment via `tests/ci-post-failure.sh`.

## 4. The no-shared-lib policy

**Guide.** State the package's runtime dependencies on
sibling scripts (ideally: none). Reference the FEAT that
established the policy. Warn future contributors against
"DRY-ing it up" by reaching back into sibling packages.

**Example (account).**
`account` is the foundation. Every line of code it needs
is right here — no calls to other scripts in the
collection at runtime. The only declared dependency is
`rpk` for deployment metadata, never invoked at runtime
(FEAT-022).

## 5. What is intentionally duplicated

**Guide.** List the snippets lifted from sibling packages
that the no-shared-lib policy forces into this repo. For
each, note which sibling it came from and that bug-fixes
propagate by re-implementation, not by import.

**Example (account).**
- **cache-home / config-home / data-home computation** —
  same shape as the corresponding `cache` / `config` /
  `data` functions, inlined here.
- **Platform detection** (`account platform`) — same logic
  as `cluster node platform`, intentionally duplicated.
- **GPG / SSH key handling** — direct calls to `gpg(1)`
  and `ssh-keygen(1)`; never delegated to `secret` or
  `crypt`.

## 6. Consumers

**Guide.** List the other packages in the collection that
declare `.rpk/depends/<this-package>` and call this
package at runtime. This is the "who breaks if we break
the CLI contract" inventory.

**Example (account).**
Every other script in the collection: `config`, `data`,
`secret`, `crypt`, `repo`, `event`, `services`, `check`,
`user`, `cluster`, `bitcoin`, `lightning`, `dht`, … each
declares `.rpk/depends/account` and calls `account` for
identity / endpoint / GPG-encrypt / SSH-exec needs.

## 7. Build / install

**Guide.** One paragraph: how does the package install?
Reference the autoconf umbrella (FEAT-191), the stow-based
linking, and the always-installable-master invariant.

**Example (account).**
`./configure && make install` (autoconf umbrella per
FEAT-191). Stow-based install. `master` is always
installable; releases are tagged via `.rpk/version`.

## 8. Versioning

**Guide.** Restate the semver + TSV-ledger conventions.
Point at `.rpk/version` and `.rpk/versions`. Note the
"no orphan SHAs" rule from rpk's BUG-001.

**Example (account).**
Semver. Every release is recorded in `.rpk/versions`
(TSV ledger — no orphan SHAs per rpk's BUG-001 lesson).
The `version` builtin returns the current `.rpk/version`.

## 9. Testing institutions

**Guide.** Reference `skills/testing.md` and summarise the
three test layers (unit / SIT / PIT), the pre-push runner,
and the CI failure-to-PR-comment channel. State the agent
contract: pre-push gate before every push.

**Example (account).**
See `skills/testing.md`. Three layers: unit
(`tests/unit/*.bats`), SIT (`tests/sit/`), PIT
(`tests/pit/`, reserved). One pre-push entry:
`tests/pre-push.sh`. CI posts failing-job log tails to
the PR.

## 10. Logging

**Guide.** Reference `skills/logging.md`. State the five
levels, the gates (`<SELF>_DEBUG`, `<SELF>_QUIET`), and
the source-only-mode envvar used by tests.

**Example (account).**
See `skills/logging.md`. Five levels: debug → info → warn
→ error → fatal. `SELF_DEBUG` gates debug; `SELF_QUIET`
silences info. `ACCOUNT_SOURCE_ONLY=1` lets unit tests
source the script.

## 11. Auto-merge

**Guide.** Reference `skills/automerging.md`. State the
draft → green → ready → squash lifecycle and the
subscribe-and-end-turn rule.

**Example (account).**
See `skills/automerging.md`. Draft → green CI → ready →
squash-merge. After every push the agent **subscribes**
(`subscribe_pr_activity`) and **ends the turn**. No
polling.

## 12. Milestones and audits

**Guide.** Reference `skills/milestones.md` and
`skills/audit.md`. State the one-session-per-milestone
rule, the move-to-done convention, and the
delete-completed-ROADMAP rule.

**Example (account).**
See `skills/milestones.md` and `skills/audit.md`.
`issues/ROADMAP-<X.Y.Z>.md` groups bugs and features that
will land in one release. Completed ROADMAPs are deleted;
`status: done` issues move to `issues/{bug,feature}/done/`.
Audits run after every milestone.
